<paragraph id="F8EE5A6F21D5AB1618FD058E508B8073" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Measurements.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="976E7A39030685044D99B102770BFA49" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">BL = 3.25-3.60 mm, BW = 2.02-2.24 mm, HL = 0.91 mm, HW = 0.91 mm, PL = 1.08 mm, PW = 2.02 mm, EL = 2.00 mm, AL = 0.87 mm, AW = 0.27 mm, SL = 0.41 mm.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="989AC0BD919EE8815194BAE325C2D4BC" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" type="description">
<paragraph id="82B7956188B8F80F39577CF0767C05A2" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="89B9E31DB5D37A0F606738A100317F14" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
Body (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="96DB355F20419B1820A525B68723E8DC" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Melixanthus menglaensis Duan, Wang &amp; Zhou, sp. nov. A, C habitus B, D lateral view of habitus E head F antennae G ventral view of habitus. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A-E, G), 0.2 mm (F)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1060.70203.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/589885" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">3A-D</figureCitation>
) elongate, almost cylindrical, rounded anteriorly. Head (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="32C9272E5DF530EA5BB7E6E143D0788A" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Melixanthus menglaensis Duan, Wang &amp; Zhou, sp. nov. A, C habitus B, D lateral view of habitus E head F antennae G ventral view of habitus. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A-E, G), 0.2 mm (F)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1060.70203.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/589885" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">3E</figureCitation>
) yellow, vertex with a darkish brown M-shaped marking; antennae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="6E4B10D8F9E5F8FD693892FC8C68C237" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Melixanthus menglaensis Duan, Wang &amp; Zhou, sp. nov. A, C habitus B, D lateral view of habitus E head F antennae G ventral view of habitus. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A-E, G), 0.2 mm (F)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1060.70203.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/589885" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">3F</figureCitation>
) with basal 5 segments yellowish brown, terminal 6 segments reddish brown; clypeus yellow; labrum yellowish brown; mandibles darkish brown. Pronotum yellow, with two pitchy brown subtriangular markings along anterior margin. Scutellum yellow and margins black. Elytra pitchy brown, with a yellowish-brown band in middle region, covering about 1/2 of whole region; margins pitchy brown. Sometimes entirely yellow, only margins pitchy brown. Ventral surface yellow, metasternum with a rectangular black marking. Legs and pygidium all yellow.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9CDB66AB793ADE09E7A82B55A9D3B08F" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
Head (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="139449801E0CA81201360A0F06676EBE" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Melixanthus menglaensis Duan, Wang &amp; Zhou, sp. nov. A, C habitus B, D lateral view of habitus E head F antennae G ventral view of habitus. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A-E, G), 0.2 mm (F)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1060.70203.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/589885" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">3E</figureCitation>
) densely and coarsely punctate, flattened on midline, longitudinally impressed on frons and vertex. Eyes kidney-shaped, deeply emarginated; antennal insertions a little more widely separated than superior eye-lobes. Clypeus sparsely punctate, strongly arcuate on anterior margin. Antennae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="26546007FF619AD2F0DC8D99B1E1F332" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Melixanthus menglaensis Duan, Wang &amp; Zhou, sp. nov. A, C habitus B, D lateral view of habitus E head F antennae G ventral view of habitus. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A-E, G), 0.2 mm (F)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1060.70203.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/589885" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">3F</figureCitation>
) with sparsely long hair, short and slightly broad, reaching humeral tubercle; 1st segment clubbed; 2nd oblong, about half as long as 1st; 3rd-5th thin, about equal in length, longer than 2nd; 6 apical segments moderately thickened, about 2.0-2.2 times as long as wide, last segment pointed apically.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4C1B2E316FA26E85F76A08C26B4C066D" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
Pronotum (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="AAE5C628F3D6BF7E7B7AC8E4FED51559" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Melixanthus menglaensis Duan, Wang &amp; Zhou, sp. nov. A, C habitus B, D lateral view of habitus E head F antennae G ventral view of habitus. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A-E, G), 0.2 mm (F)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1060.70203.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/589885" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">3A-D</figureCitation>
) 1.8 times as wide as long, moderately narrowed and rounded anteriorly; surface strongly convex, impunctate and shining. Scutellum triangular, nearly as long as wide, surface smooth, shining.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4A93DC973F418903C265D630CAC2DAC7" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
Elytron (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="D5B20051C032804A8BB0EC1AAC12F00D" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Melixanthus menglaensis Duan, Wang &amp; Zhou, sp. nov. A, C habitus B, D lateral view of habitus E head F antennae G ventral view of habitus. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A-E, G), 0.2 mm (F)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1060.70203.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/589885" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">3A-D</figureCitation>
) parallel-sides, apical margin slightly straight, 2.0 times as long as wide, humeri prominent and glabrous. Disc with regular rows of fine punctures, partly confused near apical slope; interspaces without punctures; epipleurae slightly obliquely placed and seen in lateral view.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1E19F3894C3B2CADDB990A636870A105" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
Ventral side (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="92B7EB2963036A5F6CA6E94BE877F3BE" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Melixanthus menglaensis Duan, Wang &amp; Zhou, sp. nov. A, C habitus B, D lateral view of habitus E head F antennae G ventral view of habitus. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A-E, G), 0.2 mm (F)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1060.70203.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/589885" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">3G</figureCitation>
) partly clothed with pubescence. Prosternum (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="7313C70250729D3E93698DE13A93B0BB" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Melixanthus prosternum A, B M. menglaensis Duan, Wang &amp; Zhou, sp. nov. C, D M. similibimaculicollis Duan, Wang &amp; Zhou, sp. nov. E, F M. bimaculicollis Baly, 1865." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1060.70203.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/589883" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">1A, B</figureCitation>
) square, anterior margin slightly concave; basal margin nearly straight, and drawn out into a pair of small denticles. Mesosternum trapeziform, twice as wide as long. Metasternum wrinkled at sutural region and with dense pubescence. Pygidium flat, punctate and pubescent. Claws (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="D4522BE32FF53987DAE3358963D75C8B" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Melixanthus claws A, B M. menglaensis Duan, Wang &amp; Zhou, sp. nov. C, D M. similibimaculicollis Duan, Wang &amp; Zhou, sp. nov. E, F M. bimaculicollis Baly, 1865. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1060.70203.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/589884" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">2A, B</figureCitation>
) not toothed, thickened basally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7ABAC6C0740570894326D21879A78007" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
<emphasis id="2211E6921E44BFA5D72D5A2F5C115098" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Aedeagus</emphasis>
(Figs 
<figureCitation id="0E57088545CDD82B420743B2AE24C642" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Melixanthus menglaensis Duan, Wang &amp; Zhou, sp. nov. A lateral view of aedeagus B dorsal view of aedeagus C ventral view of aedeagus D spermatheca E female rectal pad. Scale bars: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1060.70203.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/589886" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">4A-C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="A5A5E89DE28AD6EC26D2988156B6715E" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Melixanthus menglaensis Duan, Wang &amp; Zhou, sp. nov. A dorsal view of aedeagus B ventral view of aedeagus C lateral view of aedeagus D spermatheca. Scale bars: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1060.70203.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/589887" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">5A-C</figureCitation>
) elongate, about 3.2 times as long as wide, clubbed. Apex of median lobe narrower than middle, acute at apex, slightly curved in lateral view; with several pubescence on each side of apex and upper lateral margins, punctate on ventral side of upper middle part. Median orifice with middle sclerite bending inwards above surface. Upper part of median lobe with a pair of sclerotized prominence, exceeding the median lobe. Inner sac rather narrow, arrow-shaped. Tegmen Y-shaped, weakly sclerotized, almost translucent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="633E26FD15B70A8B421237CFE950EE37" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
<emphasis id="AB18985550DE97E3C67100BCD446A901" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Female.</emphasis>
Body more robust than male; 
<emphasis id="E471E648CDEC2419F9F8D51B1625C0D8" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">spermatheca</emphasis>
(Figs 
<figureCitation id="C9293AB2C4424C21D4309D798A013CB1" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Melixanthus menglaensis Duan, Wang &amp; Zhou, sp. nov. A lateral view of aedeagus B dorsal view of aedeagus C ventral view of aedeagus D spermatheca E female rectal pad. Scale bars: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1060.70203.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/589886" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">4D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="06FE4F2AA7C919D340E7B9D18F4C7182" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Melixanthus menglaensis Duan, Wang &amp; Zhou, sp. nov. A dorsal view of aedeagus B ventral view of aedeagus C lateral view of aedeagus D spermatheca. Scale bars: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1060.70203.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/589887" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">5D</figureCitation>
) hook-shaped, bent in a right-angle halfway, slightly acute at apex; duct weakly sclerotized, irregularly coiling 9-12 times. 
<emphasis id="26E460328872D6DAB6649488EF466D03" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Rectal sclerites</emphasis>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="2E1031DC59B6961001515F9C672774BB" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Melixanthus menglaensis Duan, Wang &amp; Zhou, sp. nov. A lateral view of aedeagus B dorsal view of aedeagus C ventral view of aedeagus D spermatheca E female rectal pad. Scale bars: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1060.70203.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/589886" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">4E</figureCitation>
) weakly sclerotized, slightly connected between two rectangular sclerites on ventral side.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="937089E282F68C2383B35E1F2B912D59" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="F3B1417F9AC7D887A7A37E620EF8CA78" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6507577D9898B008F1A97376B202BB4A" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">China (Yunnan); Vietnam (Tonkin).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6B47393D1937F2A4F1F3EEE74A12A4E4" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="542DCFC28C2216584EBC15C2177F1F08" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="32BBBBFE40B1F91C45A2CE649A2894B4" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">The specific epithet is derived from the name (Pinyin) of the type locality, Mengla.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C81693DC53779C3E4CC80E97F069DDD7" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="675BDFD36D7703C4EFF0E3F791A5A3F2" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="493E0EFC1FFF749DA0FF8AAEC2DF677B" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="0F38F30D9762802CBE4F700C5AA107B3" genus="M." lsidName="M. bimaculicollis" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="bimaculicollis">
<emphasis id="D37295F6695114B1F68788F9B9210856" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">M. bimaculicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Baly, 1865, but can be distinguished from that species in having finer punctures on the head, a narrower pronotum, an impunctate scutellum, and fine puncture rows on the elytra, whereas 
<taxonomicName id="ACABEFA3316D83FA540359E7AF43D39F" genus="M." lsidName="M. bimaculicollis" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="bimaculicollis">
<emphasis id="626B06843397AA5A0429102497955C73" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">M. bimaculicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the elytra with distinct punctures and a surrounded by dark ring; its claws are not toothed (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="CDC5541993F32F79C5772E6D56964A86" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Melixanthus claws A, B M. menglaensis Duan, Wang &amp; Zhou, sp. nov. C, D M. similibimaculicollis Duan, Wang &amp; Zhou, sp. nov. E, F M. bimaculicollis Baly, 1865. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1060.70203.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/589884" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">2A, B</figureCitation>
) and the basal margin of its prosternum is drawn out into a pair of small, sharp denticles (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="2951FECD150D1BD305077E10929203C5" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Melixanthus prosternum A, B M. menglaensis Duan, Wang &amp; Zhou, sp. nov. C, D M. similibimaculicollis Duan, Wang &amp; Zhou, sp. nov. E, F M. bimaculicollis Baly, 1865." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1060.70203.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/589883" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">1A, B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
